<DOC><DOCNO> AP880707-0177 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-07-88 0118EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   07-07 0563</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0590</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The nation's grain reserves are large enoughto prevent major shortages for the rest of the year and keepconsumer food prices in check despite the drought, an AgricultureDepartment official says.   However, there could be a squeeze in the supply of soybeans andoats, according to Ewen M. Wilson, assistant secretary ofagriculture for economics.   Wilson said Wednesday that 65 percent of the winter wheat crop,which amounts to three-quarters of all U.S. wheat production,already has been harvested. Almost two-thirds of the spring wheatcrop is rated in poor condition because of the drought, he said.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Japan was the only industrial power to bestthe United States in reducing manufacturing labor costs in absoluteterms last year, according to a government report.   Measured in devalued U.S. dollars, labor costs in Japan soared13.5 percent compared with a 1.5 percent decline in the UnitedStates, the Labor Department reported Wednesday.   U.S. manufacturers held hourly wage and benefit increases lastyear to just 1.3 percent, compared with boosts of 1.4 percent inJapan, 4.5 percent in Candada, 3.4 percent in France, 4 percent inWest Germany and 8.2 percent in Great Britain.</TEXT><DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   World oil prices rose amid reports thatthree OPEC members might request an emergency meeting of the cartelto consider ways of cutting production and propping up prices.   But analysts remained steadfast in their predictions that thefractured cartel could do little to forestall continued priceerosion through the summer.   Prices have dropped sharply over the past month in response tosurplus supplies and a perception among traders that OPEC iscrumbling. The next regular OPEC meeting is set for Nov. 21.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Senate voted Wednesday by a veto-proof72-23 margin to make companies provide workers and local officials60 days advance notice of plant closings and large layoffs.   Nineteen Republicans, many of them up for re-election this year,joined Democrats in support of the mandatory notices, whichPresident Reagan cited as his primary reason for vetoing in May amassive overhaul of the nation's trade laws.   The bill requires employers to provide the advance notices forany shutdown of an operation involving at least one-third ofplant's workforce and any layoff applying to 50 or more workers.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eastern Airlines and its unions have signed anagreement designed to defuse years of bitter battling and improvesafety procedures at the often-criticized carrier.   The pact comes a month after federal investigators warned thatsafety could be threatened.   The deal, reached late Tuesday night, spells out procedures forthe company and its 32,500 workers to discuss complaints anddisagreements, but does little to directly address the airline'songoing negotiations with its mechanics and pilots, who are workingunder expired contracts.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Soybean futures prices surged while grain futures finished mixedWednesday amid uncertainty over the potential for further droughtdamage.   Stock prices fell on a late wave of selling. The Dow Jonesaverage of 30 industrials, up 27.03 on Tuesday, finished down 28.45to 2,130.16.   The dollar eased slightly in lackluster trading marked bycentral bank intervention. Gold prices were little changed.   Bond prices fell. The yield on the Treasury's closely watched30-year bond soared to 8.98 percent from 8.87 percent late Tuesday.</TEXT></DOC>